How the API actually works
An LLM API call is an HTTP POST. The request body contains a list of messages (a conversation history), the model name, and a few parameters. The response body contains the model’s reply. In R, httr2 handles this with no wrapper packages needed:
httr2::request("https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions") |&gt;
  httr2::req_auth_bearer_token(Sys.getenv("OPENAI_API_KEY")) |&gt;
  httr2::req_body_json(list(
    model       = "gpt-4o-mini",
    temperature = 0,
    response_format = list(type = "json_object"),
    messages = list(
      list(role = "system", content = "You are a financial analyst. Return JSON."),
      list(role = "user",   content = "Classify the sentiment of: 'record profits'")
    )
  )) |&gt;
  httr2::req_perform() |&gt;
  httr2::resp_body_json()
Three parameters matter most:

temperature: controls randomness. 0 = deterministic (same input, same output, every time). 1 = creative. For classification and extraction tasks: always 0.
response_format = list(type = "json_object"): tells the model it must return a valid JSON object. Without this, the model sometimes includes prose around the JSON and your parser breaks.
model: gpt-4o-mini is the cheap option (roughly 100× cheaper than GPT-4o). Use it for classification and extraction. Use GPT-4o or GPT-o1 when reasoning quality matters.
